5 A BILL
6 TO BE ENTITLED
7 AN ACT
8
9 Relating to food banks; to establish an income tax
10 credit for donations of edible farm products to a qualifying
11 food bank.
12 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
13 Section 1. (a) This act, the purpose of which is to
14 incentivize farmers and owners of food establishments to
15 donate certain food products to food banks, shall be known and
16 may be cited as the "Farm-to-Food Bank Act of 2026."
17 (b) As used in this act, the following terms have the
18 following meanings:
19 (1) DEPARTMENT. The Department of Agriculture and
20 Industries.
21 (2) EDIBLE FARM PRODUCTS. Plants and animals useful to
22 humans for consumption which include, but are not limited to,
23 forage and sod crops, oilseeds, grain and feed crops, dairy
24 and dairy products, poultry and poultry products, livestock,
25 fruits, and vegetables. The products may not be damaged,
26 out-of-condition, or declared unfit for human consumption by a
27 federal, state, or local health official.
28 (3) ELIGIBLE DONOR. A farmer or owner of a food
Page 1

(3) ELIGIBLE DONOR. A farmer or owner of a food
HB175 Engrossed
29 establishment.
30 (4) FARMER. An Alabama taxpayer that meets either of
31 the following qualifications:
32 a. Is responsible for and derives income of at least
33 one thousand dollars ($1,000) from growing fruits, vegetables,
34 or other edible farm products or from raising beef, poultry,
35 pork, fish, or other edible agriculture products.
36 b. Has filed an acreage report with the United States
37 Department of Agriculture.
38 (5) FOOD ESTABLISHMENT. As defined by the United States
39 Food and Drug Administration and adopted by Rule 420-3-22.01
40 of the Alabama Department of Public Health.
41 (6) QUALIFYING FOOD BANK. Any entity located within
42 Alabama that is a partner or affiliate food bank of the
43 Feeding America national food bank network or their subsidiary
44 distribution organizations.
45 (c) A credit is allowed against the state income tax
46 imposed by Section 40-18-2, Code of Alabama 1975, for eligible
47 donors who donate edible farm products to a food bank. The tax
48 credit shall equal the lesser of:
49 (1) Fifteen percent of the value of the edible farm
50 products donated during the tax year for which the credit is
51 claimed. The value of the edible farm products shall be
52 determined in the same manner as a charitable contribution of
53 food for federal tax purposes under 26 U.S.C. § 8170(e)(3)(C);
54 or
55 (2) Five thousand dollars ($5,000).
56 (d) The taxpayer claiming a tax credit under this act
Page 2

(d) The taxpayer claiming a tax credit under this act
HB175 Engrossed
57 shall not receive remuneration for the donation. The tax
58 credit must be taken in the tax year in which the taxpayer was
59 issued a tax credit certificate under subsection (g). The tax
60 credit issued under this act may not decrease a taxpayer's
61 liability to less than zero. If the tax liability of the
62 taxpayer is less than the tax credit issued under this act,
63 the taxpayer may only utilize the amount of the credit that
64 reduces the taxpayer's liability to zero. The tax credit is
65 not refundable nor transferable and may not be carried
66 forward. A taxpayer applying for the tax credit shall only
67 apply for the tax credit for the year in which the edible farm
68 products were donated to a qualifying food bank, regardless of
69 the tax liability of the taxpayer. Nothing in this section
70 shall allow any item to be deducted more than once.
71 (e) The Department of Revenue shall grant the tax
72 credit against the state income tax that is due by the
73 taxpayer holding the tax credit certificate issued under
74 subsection (g) in the amount stated on the tax credit
75 certificate, subject to the limitations of subsection (d). The
76 department may audit and reassess any credit improperly
77 obtained by the taxpayer in accordance with the Alabama
78 Taxpayers' Bill of Rights and Uniform Revenue Procedures Act,
79 Chapter 2A of Title 40 of the Code of Alabama 1975.
80 (f) The tax credit authorized by this act is limited to
81 an aggregate amount for all taxpayers of two million dollars
82 ($2,000,000) annually.
83 (g)(1) Prior to claiming the income tax credit
84 authorized under subsection (c), the taxpayer shall file an
